The use of quicklime disinfectants led to the discharge of a large amount of strong alkaline disinfection (dissolved Ca(OH)2) into the mangrove ecosystem. The composition of the marine system is complex, and the chemicals that can react with Ca(OH)2 include acidic compounds in the mangrove water such as organic acids used in shrimp pond aquaculture, weak acidic disinfectants (the main byproduct is HClO), acidic phosphorus compounds, and CO2 in seawater. According to their reaction equation with calcium hydroxide, the reaction amount of Ca(OH)2 under different pathways can be obtained, as shown in the following equation:9\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
